Education and schooling can have a significant impact on issues of inequity because they can both perpetuate and reduce existing social and structural inequities in society. On the one hand, education has the potential to perpetuate existing social and structural inequities by reproducing existing power dynamics and favoring some students while leaving others behind. Students from low-income families and students of color, for example, are more likely to attend under-resourced schools with fewer academic and extracurricular opportunities, which can lead to lower academic achievement and graduation rates. Education, on the other hand, has the potential to reduce existing social and structural inequalities by providing individuals with the knowledge, skills, and abilities required to function in society, as well as opportunities for social and economic advancement. Education can also help to promote social change by equipping people with the critical thinking skills they need to challenge existing power dynamics and work for social justice. Education also contributes significantly to the accumulation of human, social, and cultural capital. Human capital refers to the knowledge, skills, and abilities that people gain through education and training that can boost their economic productivity and earning potential. Individuals' social capital refers to the networks and resources to which they have access, which can increase their economic productivity and earning potential. Cultural capital refers to the knowledge, skills, and abilities that people gain through education and training, which can help them advance in their social and economic lives. Overall, depending on how education is structured and implemented, education and schooling can have both positive and negative implications for issues of inequity. Education has the potential to perpetuate existing social and structural inequities by reproducing existing power dynamics and giving some students advantages while leaving others behind. Education, on the other hand, has the potential to reduce existing social and structural inequities by providing individuals with the knowledge, skills, and abilities required to function in society, as well as opportunities for social and economic advancement. Education also contributes significantly to the accumulation of human, social, and cultural capital. 